The accident involved an experimental amateur-built RANS S12XL airplane.
The airplane's registration number was N73KA.
The accident occurred at Arthur Dunn Air Park (X21) in Titusville, Florida.
The airplane was substantially damaged in the accident.
The private pilot was not injured in the accident.

The left main gear impacted the ground while the pilot attempted to flare and land.
The airplane flipped over after impact.
The airplane came to rest inverted.
The cockpit was crushed upward during the accident.
The fuselage was crushed upward during the accident.
Both horizontal stabilizers were bent upward.
Both horizontal stabilizers were buckled.
Examination of the engine revealed no anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
Examination of the engine components revealed no anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
Several successful engine runs were conducted during the examination.
The pilot held a Private pilot certificate.
The pilot was 65 years old.
The pilot was female.
The pilot held a Single-engine land airplane rating.
The pilot occupied the left seat during the flight.
The pilot had no other aircraft ratings.
The pilot used a 3-point restraint system.
The pilot held an Instrument rating for airplanes.
No second pilot was present during the flight.
The pilot had no instructor ratings.
No toxicology was performed on the pilot.
The pilot held a Class 3 Medical Certification without waivers or limitations.

text:
# Factual Information

## History of Flight

Initial climb | Loss of engine power (total) (Defining event)

On January 16, 2020, about 1330 eastern standard time, an experimental amateur-built RANS S12XL airplane, N73KA, was substantially damaged when it was involved in an accident at Arthur Dunn Air Park (X21), Titusville, Florida. The private pilot was not injured. The airplane was operated as a personal flight under the provisions of Title 14 Code of Federal Regulations Part 91.

According to the pilot, during the initial climbout about 200 ft above ground level, the engine stopped. The pilot made a 180 descending left turn, while maintaining 60 mph. While attempting to flare and land, the nose and left main gear impacted the ground. The airplane flipped over and came to rest inverted.

Examination of the airplane revealed that the cockpit and fuselage were crushed upward. Both horizontal stabilizers were bent upward and buckled. Examination of the engine and its components, which included several successful engine runs, revealed no anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
